1.2 Fundamental Constraints

1.2.1 Radiative Heat Transfer Constraint

Theorem 1.1 (Radiative Limit). For an OCN with radiator area A_r and emissivity \epsilon, the maximum sustainable compute power P_c^{max} is:

P_c^{max}(t) = \epsilon \sigma A_r [T_s(t)^4 - T_{env}(t)^4] - \alpha A_s \Phi(t) - \frac{dQ_{pcm}}{dt}

where \sigma = 5.67 \times 10^{-8} \text{ W/m}^2\text{K}^4 and \alpha is solar absorptivity.

Proof. From energy conservation:

P_c + P_{solar,abs} = P_{rad} + \frac{dQ_{pcm}}{dt} + \frac{dU}{dt}

where U is internal energy. In steady-state, dU/dt = 0, and P_{rad} = \epsilon \sigma A_r (T_s^4 - T_{env}^4). Solar absorbed power P_{solar,abs} = \alpha A_s \Phi. Rearranging gives the result. ∎

Corollary 1.1.1. For fixed T_s^{max} = 358K and T_{env} \approx 4K:

P_c^{max} \approx 1.37 \times 10^{-6} \epsilon A_r (T_s^{max})^4 \approx 2.01 \epsilon A_r \text{ kW}

Thus each m² of radiator supports ~2 kW of computation at 85°C.

