1.4.2 Model Predictive Control (MPC) Algorithm

Algorithm 1.1 (Orbital-Aware MPC).

```
Input: Current state x(t), disturbance forecast o(t..t+H), model f
Output: Optimal control sequence u*(t..t+H)

1. while mission active do:
2.   Measure x(t)
3.   Retrieve predicted o(t..t+H) from orbital ephemeris
4.   Solve optimization: u* = argmax J(x,u,o) subject to constraints
5.   Apply first control action u*(t)
6.   t ← t + Δt
7.   Update model with observed state transitions
8. end while
```

Theorem 1.3 (MPC Stability). The MPC controller with horizon H \geq T_{orbit} and terminal constraint x(t+H) \in \mathcal{X}_{safe} is asymptotically stable for the OCN system.

Proof Sketch. The orbital disturbance o(t) is periodic with period T_{orbit}. By choosing H \geq T_{orbit}, we ensure each optimization sees a complete cycle. The terminal constraint ensures recursive feasibility. Using standard MPC stability results (Rawlings & Mayne, 2009), asymptotic stability follows. ∎

