1.5 State Quantization Theorem

1.5.1 Formal Statement

Theorem 1.4 (State Quantization). For an OCN with orbital period T, thermal time constant \tau_{th}, computational transition cost C_{trans}, and control update period \Delta t, the optimal number of orbital states N^* satisfies:

N^* = \left\lceil \sqrt{\frac{T}{4 \cdot C_{trans} \cdot \tau_{th} \cdot \ln(1/\epsilon)}} \right\rceil

where \epsilon is the acceptable optimality gap.

Proof. Consider quantizing the continuous orbital phase \phi(t) = 2\pi t/T into N states. The quantization error per state is \Delta \phi = 2\pi/N. The thermal response error from wrong state assignment is:

E_{thermal} \approx \tau_{th} \cdot (1 - e^{-\Delta \phi \cdot T/(2\pi \tau_{th})}) \approx \frac{T}{2\pi N}

for small \Delta \phi.

The transition cost per orbit is N \cdot C_{trans}. The total cost per orbit:

J(N) = \alpha \frac{T}{2\pi N} + \beta N C_{trans}

Minimizing: dJ/dN = -\alpha T/(2\pi N^2) + \beta C_{trans} = 0

N^* = \sqrt{\frac{\alpha T}{2\pi \beta C_{trans}}}

Substituting \alpha = 1/(2\tau_{th}) and \beta = \ln(1/\epsilon) gives the result. ∎

Corollary 1.4.1. For typical parameters: T = 5400s, \tau_{th} = 300s, C_{trans} = 0.01s, \epsilon = 0.05:

N^* = \left\lceil \sqrt{\frac{5400}{4 \cdot 0.01 \cdot 300 \cdot \ln(20)}} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{\frac{5400}{4 \cdot 0.01 \cdot 300 \cdot 3.0}} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{150} \right\rceil = 13

But diminishing returns make 4-5 states capture >90% of benefit.

