1.6 PCM Optimization

1.6.1 Optimal PCM Mass

Theorem 1.6 (PCM Mass Optimization). For an OCN with peak-to-average power ratio r = P_{peak}/P_{avg} and orbital period T, the optimal PCM mass m_{pcm}^* is:

m_{pcm}^* = \frac{(r-1)P_{avg} \cdot t_{sun}}{L \cdot \eta_{pcm}}

where t_{sun} = (1-f_e)T is sunlight duration, L is latent heat, and \eta_{pcm} is PCM efficiency.

Proof. The PCM must store excess energy during peak computation:

E_{store} = (P_{peak} - P_{avg}) \cdot t_{compute}

Assuming computation occurs during sunlight: t_{compute} \approx t_{sun}. The PCM storage capacity is m_{pcm} L \eta_{pcm}. Equating gives the result. ∎

Example: For P_{peak} = 40kW, P_{avg} = 25kW, t_{sun} = 3500s, L = 200kJ/kg, \eta_{pcm} = 0.8:

m_{pcm}^* = \frac{(1.6-1)\cdot 25000 \cdot 3500}{200000 \cdot 0.8} = \frac{0.6\cdot 25000\cdot 3500}{160000} = 328 \text{ kg}

