1.7 Radiation Reliability Model

1.7.1 Fault Rate Model

The radiation-induced fault rate follows a Poisson process with time-varying rate:

\lambda_{SEE}(t) = \lambda_0 \cdot \exp\left(-\frac{R_{shield}}{R_0}\right) \cdot f_{orbit}(t)

where R_{shield} is shielding thickness, R_0 is characteristic length, and f_{orbit}(t) accounts for position in radiation belts.

1.7.2 Optimal Checkpoint Interval

Theorem 1.7 (Dynamic Checkpointing). For time-varying fault rate \lambda(t), the optimal checkpoint interval t_c^*(t) minimizes expected time to completion:

t_c^*(t) = \sqrt{\frac{2C_{ckpt}}{\bar{\lambda}(t)}}

where \bar{\lambda}(t) = \frac{1}{t_c} \int_t^{t+t_c} \lambda(\tau) d\tau is the average rate over the interval.

Proof. Generalization of Young/Daly formula. The expected time for a task of duration T with checkpoint overhead C and failure rate \lambda is:

E[T] = \frac{T}{t_c} (t_c + C) e^{\lambda t_c}

Minimizing gives t_c = \sqrt{2C/\lambda}. For time-varying \lambda, use local average. ∎

