4. Mathematical Appendix

4.1 Derivation of Thermal Dynamics

Starting from first principles:

C_{th} \frac{dT}{dt} = P_{in} - P_{out}

where:

P_{in} = P_{compute} + \alpha A_s \Phi(t) + P_{dissipation}

P_{out} = \epsilon \sigma A_r (T^4 - T_{env}^4) + P_{conduction} + P_{convection}

In space, P_{conduction} \approx 0 (vacuum), P_{convection} = 0. Thus:

C_{th} \frac{dT}{dt} = P_{compute} + \alpha A_s \Phi(t) - \epsilon \sigma A_r (T^4 - T_{env}^4)

Adding PCM:

C_{th} \frac{dT}{dt} = P_{compute} + \alpha A_s \Phi(t) - \epsilon \sigma A_r (T^4 - T_{env}^4) - \frac{dQ_{pcm}}{dt}

where:

\frac{dQ_{pcm}}{dt} = 
\begin{cases}
k_{melt}(T - T_{melt}) & \text{if } T > T_{melt} \text{ and } Q < Q_{max} \\
k_{freeze}(T_{melt} - T) & \text{if } T < T_{melt} \text{ and } Q > 0 \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

